ce:section.ce:para:
To obtain optimal analytical performance, the effect of several crucial parameters on the proposed detection system was investigated. Both the fluorescence quenching of BCDs and the oxidation of OPD were related to MnO2 NSs. As shown in Fig. S7, the fluorescence intensity of BCDs was decreased sharply with the increase of the concentration of MnO2 NSs. When the concentration was higher than 80 μM, the decrease tended to be gentle. It was worth noting that a high concentration of MnO2 NSs may also lead to the decrease of fluorescence emission of DAP due to the wide absorption band of MnO2 NSs (
                        Fig. S4
                        ). Based on these considerations, a low concentration of 50 μM was employed in the next experiments, which could quench the fluorescence of BCDs to a great extent and meanwhile had a negative effect on the fluorescence of DAP. Other parameters such as the concentration of OPD and SOD, the decomposition time of MnO2 NSs, as well as the incubation time of MnO2 NSs with OPD were all carefully optimized (details provided in Supporting information Fig. S8).
